{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01EChydhyQFAjsFikXiX32TV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the source file and convert it to a knowledge file JSON.\n\n**Step 1: Identify the title**\nThe title is: 携帯端末(フィーチャーフォン)向け画面を実装する際の留意点\n\n**Step 1.5: Check for no-knowledge-content**\nThe source has meaningful content - a feature support table and a list of unsupported custom tags. This has Layer A and Layer B content. Set `no_knowledge_content: false`.\n\n**Step 2: Build the section list**\nLooking for h2 headings (underlined with `-----`):\n1. \"携帯端末でサポートされるNablarchの機能\" (underlined with `=====` - wait, that's h2 in RST context since the document title uses `===`)\n\n\n2. \"本項で説明する内容\" (underlined with `---`)\n\nI need to clarify the RST heading hierarchy here. The document title uses overline and underline with `=`, then the sections use `=` and `-` for underlines. Looking at the actual structure, `=` underlines indicate h2 and `-` underlines indicate h3. Looking at the actual RST structure more carefully now — the document title uses both overline and underline with `===`, then \"本項で説明する内容\" has both overline and underline with `---`, and the subsequent sections like \"携帯端末でサポートされるNablarchの機能\" and \"携帯端末で使用できないカスタムタグライブラリ\" use only underlines with `===`. So the hierarchy appears to be: title at the top level, then the dashed sections are h2, and the equals-underline-only sections are also h2 or possibly h3 depending on RST's interpretation of which marker was introduced first as a sub-level. Looking at the document structure, I can see there are three main sections: an introductory \"本項で説明する内容\" marked with `--`, followed by two primary content sections both marked with `===`. The intro is quite brief, so the real content splits happen at those two main sections with `===` underlines. I'll use those h2-level headings as my split points for organizing the document. Looking at the RST source more carefully, I see the distinction now. The section with dashes both above and below uses `---`, while the other section uses `===` as an underline only. The rule specifies \"Text line followed by `-----` underline,\" but neither of these examples strictly matches that pattern—one has overline and underline with dashes, the other has just an underline with equals signs. I need to figure out which one actually qualifies as the h2 heading according to the rules. I'm working through the RST heading hierarchy in this Nablarch documentation. The structure uses `===` for underline-only sections and `---` for overline+underline chapters, which creates some ambiguity about what constitutes h2-level splits. Looking at the actual content, I see three main sections: a brief introduction, a feature support table, and a custom tag library section—so I'll treat the latter two as the primary h2-level divisions for splitting purposes. Looking at the intro section more carefully, it's actually describing the scope of what the document covers - constraints around subwindows and other limitations for mobile devices. This seems like it should be merged into the first main section rather than kept separate, since it's foundational context rather than a standalone section. So I'll structure it as two main sections: the feature support table and the unsupported custom tags, with the intro content integrated as background. 機能テーブルには各機能の説明が含まれており、セッションスコープから複数ウィンドウの制御まで、携帯端末でサポートされる主要な機能が列挙されている。これらの内容を合わせると1000〜1500文字程度になると見込まれるため、h3見出しは不要で、現在のセクション構成のままで問題ない。\n\n導入部分「本項で説明する内容」はレイヤーCの説明とスマートフォン除外というスコープ制約を含んでいるため、これをs1に統合することで、全体の構成がより簡潔になる。\n\nセッションスコープとウィンドウスコープについては、機能テーブルのレイヤーAから、Cookie非対応端末ではURLリライトが必要という点と、`<n:a>`タグによる遷移の扱いを含める必要がある。\n\n二重サブミット防止ではサーバサイドのトークン制御のみが対応で、送信URI動的切替ではサーブレットコンテキスト外部は制御不可という制限がある。ボタン・リンクによるフォーム送信はJavaScript非対応端末では使用不可で、URIの文字列長上限（docomo は512byte）に注意が必要。\n\nファイルダウンロードやアップロード、複数ウィンドウの制御についても、カスタムタグライブラリを使用するとJSPエラーが発生するため、代替手段の検討が必要。\n\n次に、携帯端末でのNablarch機能のサポート状況を表形式でまとめていて、セッションスコープやリクエストスコープ、ウィンドウスコープなど各機能の対応状況と留意点を確認している。\n\nウィンドウスコープはデータ量を抑える必要があり、二重サブミット防止はサーバサイドのトークン制御のみで対応し、ボタン・リンクによるフォーム送信はJavaScriptが動作しない端末では実現不可なため、通常のリンクタグとクエリパラメータを使用する必要がある。\n\nクエリパラメータはURIの文字列長上限（docomo端末は512byte）に注意し、固定長・固定件数のデータのみとすること。ファイルダウンロードはリンクタグまたはオブジェクトタグを使用し、GETリクエストのみのため、フォームパラメータ送信とウィンドウスコープ維持は不可。\n\nファイルアップロードは標準的なファイル入力タグを使用するが、サポート機種が限定的なため、メール添付などの代替手段を検討する必要がある。複数ウィンドウの制御は端末側に機能がないため不可。入力画面と確認画面の共用化、認可・開閉局判定に基づく表示制御は対応可能。\n\nこれらのカスタムタグライブラリは機能制約により正常に動作せず、使用するとJSPエラーが発生する。\n\nセッションスコープやウィンドウスコープの管理、二重サブミット防止、ボタンやリンクによるフォーム送信、ファイルダウンロード・アップロード、複数ウィンドウ制御、携帯端末対応、URLリライト、トークン制御など、様々な機能に関連するタグが影響を受ける。\n\ns2ではボタン関連のタグやポップアップ送信、ダウンロード機能、携帯端末対応が重要なヒントになっている。\n\n次に、カスタムタグの使用に関してJSPエラーと使用不可タグの問題を確認する必要がある。公式ドキュメントのURLについては、ベースURLが提供されていないためJavadocの参照もないので、空の配列になる。\n\nGenerating JSON structure... Looking at the constraints for file downloads and uploads—downloads require using standard anchor or object tags since only GET requests work, which means I can't maintain form parameters or window scope, while uploads need the standard input tag and have similar limitations with parameter passing.\n\nFor multiple window control, that's completely unsupported on mobile devices, so any popup-related tags will cause errors. The table also shows that input/confirmation screen consolidation and authorization-based display control both work fine.\n\nThe custom tag library has several tags that don't work properly and will throw runtime exceptions—button, submit link, popup submit, popup link, and popup-related tags all fail when used.\n\nListing out the problematic tags...\n\nI'm working through the RST document structure now. Looking at the heading patterns, I can see there are three main sections marked with different underline styles — the first uses dashes for both overline and underline, while the other two use equals signs for underlines only. I need to figure out the proper heading hierarchy based on Nablarch's RST conventions, where equals signs typically denote the document title and dashes mark subsections. The main content should split into two sections: one covering the supported Nablarch features on mobile devices with that core feature table, and another listing the unsupported custom tag libraries. I'm also noting the Layer A context from the intro—the restrictions on subwindows and JavaScript on certain devices, plus the scope note that smartphones like iPhone and Android fall outside this document's focus.\n\nGenerating the JSON output... Looking at the constraints for file downloads and uploads—downloads require using standard anchor or object tags since only GET requests work, which means I can't maintain form parameters or window scope, while uploads need the basic file input element since support is limited to just a few devices, with email attachment being a more practical fallback option.\n\nMultiple window control isn't supported on the device side, so popup-related tags will cause errors. Input screen and confirmation screen sharing works fine, as does display control based on authorization and branch opening/closing status.\n\nThe custom tag library has several tags that don't work properly due to functional constraints—using them triggers runtime exceptions: button, submitLink, popupSubmit, popupLink, popupButton, downloadLink, and downloadButton.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22062,"cache_read_input_tokens":29955,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":22062,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5575e1d3-020c-4d75-9b39-eea914f720f7","uuid":"37f4703b-e61f-49b2-962b-67c844d924fd"}
